Traffic Stops by the Baltimore Police

Lindsay Huth

10/5/2017

We have a consent decree. Now what?

In April 2015, 25-year-old Freddie Gray died after sustaining spinal cord injuries while in police custody.

Over a year later, an investigation of the Baltimore Police Department by the U.S. Department of Justice turned up a pattern and practice of discriminatory policing behavior that violated citizens constitutional rights particularly those of blacks. In April 2017, the two agencies entered into a consent decree to repair the systemic issues.

Now what?

Can cops change? How?

Im part of a team project in conjunction with an urban affairs reporting class at UMD investigating policing practices in Baltimore, past and present.

Digging into data

My contribution: Im the sole head of a data investigation into Baltimores traffic stop records. I started in summer 2017, working under Marylands Public Information Act to request the traffic stop data from its owners, the Governors Office of Crime Control and Prevention.

For each traffic stop reported by a law enforcement agency, we have fields like the drivers race and age, the stop reason, whether the officer conducted a search and whether the search turned up anything (contraband, property or both). Check out a snippet of Baltimores stops from 2011:

I pulled Baltimores data into RStudio and expected to find what the consent decree indicated: a higher search rate for blacks and other minorities that didnt reflect the hit rate, indicating the higher searches arent in line with who is carrying contraband.

What I found instead was messy and confusing data.

Check out the number of stops reported by the Baltimore police each year (two years are missing because the law mandating data collection sunsetted during those years):

The department reported just 4,410 stops in 2009 and over 80,000 in 2013. I also calculated at the search rate (percent of stopped drivers that officers search) and the hit rate (the percent of searches that are successful, turning up contraband, property or both) for each year. Both were erratic, too. Heres a look at the hit rate:

The department reported just 36 searches in 2009, and zero hits.

For contrast, I pulled data from the region one source pointed to as the model for high-tech, data-driven policing: Los Angeles. The California data was available from the Stanford Open Policing Project, and I parsed out the stops from the county (individual departments werent given). Unlike Baltimore, the stop numbers and search rates are remarkably consistent:

Whats happening with our Baltimore data?

I circled back with the Governors Office and the Baltimore police. Baltimores data, I figured, was less reliable than the rest of the states. My sources told me its the only department, after all, that doesnt report its stops electronically through computers in its cars; instead, officers fill out paper reports, which are later manually entered by other officers too injured for patrolling.

For comparison, I pulled data from other departments, large and small, across Maryland. But instead of seeing order, like the LA stops, each Maryland department had its own confusing pattern of stops, searches and hits. Here are stop numbers from a sampling of departments:

Ive reached out to representatives from each department, and the ones Ive spoken with have said the data dont make sense and dont seem reliable but theyre not sure why.

Ive also spoken to researchers and open data advocates who have accessed the data, as well as a former legislator who sponsored the most recent version of the bill that mandated the data collection.

I dont have answers yet.

But the goal is to understand the system behind the data: why do these discrepancies exist? What does this mean for Baltimore as it tries to reform its policing patterns under the consent decree? How can the public know whats happening in police departments when data arent being accurately reported? And how can police reform without knowing where the problems exist?

Stay tuned. Ill eventually write about the impact of technology, past and present, on policing. And Ill use my design and web development background to build a timeline covering the history of police in Baltimore (forking the Knight Labs timeline.js). We have a whole team of reporters working on other aspects of policing in Baltimore, and Ill build the entire site that houses our multiplatform, many-part project.

In the meantime, Ill keep making calls and sorting through data.
